Rioting broke out in Toledo, Ohio as counter-protestors clashed with a neo-Nazi group, leading to chaos in the streets.
The police struggled to control the situation, with one officer injured during the arrests.
The presence of white supremacists disgusted many, including Mitt Romney.
The tension escalated as Mayor Jack Ford faced backlash for allowing the march.
Despite the violence, efforts were made to maintain peace during mass demonstrations.
The incident highlighted deep-rooted issues within the community, emphasizing the need for unity and respect among all races.
